# Copy to .env and fill in. These drive entrypoint.sh -> `vllm serve`.
#
# TARGET HARDWARE: single RTX 3060 (12 GB). This is tight — see the quantization
# and context notes below. fp16 weights for a 9B (~18 GB) DO NOT FIT; you must
# quantize. A smaller Qwen3.5 (3-4B class) fits far more comfortably and leaves
# room for several batched LoRA adapters — recommended for the multi-agent goal.

# vLLM image tag. PINNED (never use `latest` — it's a moving target and breaks
# reproducibility). Bump to the newest tag that supports your Qwen3.5 build; the
# entrypoint auto-detects the structured-outputs flag, so a bump stays safe.
# NB: the client library sends the modern `structured_outputs` request body, so the
# tag must be new enough to accept it (vLLM 0.10+).
VLLM_TAG=v0.11.0

# Base model: HF repo id, or a local path under /models/base (WSL2-backed `models` volume).
# vLLM needs HF-format (safetensors) weights — NOT the GGUF the llama.cpp box uses.
# Use the newest Qwen3.5. If an official AWQ/GPTQ repo exists, prefer it (faster than
# on-the-fly bnb). Otherwise point MODEL at the fp16 repo and let bitsandbytes quantize.
MODEL=Qwen/Qwen3.5-4B-Instruct        # <-- set to the exact Qwen3.5 repo you want
SERVED_MODEL_NAME=base

# Auth (enforced on every request when set).
VLLM_API_KEY=change-me

# Capacity — sized for 12 GB. Keep context modest; KV cache is the main VRAM sink.
MAX_MODEL_LEN=8192
GPU_MEMORY_UTILIZATION=0.92

# --- Quantization (REQUIRED on 12 GB) ---------------------------------------
# Option A (lowest friction, works from plain fp16 HF weights): on-the-fly 4-bit
EXTRA_ARGS=--quantization bitsandbytes --dtype half
# Option B (faster, needs a pre-quantized AWQ repo in MODEL):
# EXTRA_ARGS=--quantization awq --dtype half
# NOTE: verify LoRA + chosen quantization are compatible on the pinned VLLM_TAG
# before relying on adapters (bnb+LoRA has had rough edges).

# Constrained decoding backend.
STRUCTURED_OUTPUTS_BACKEND=xgrammar
# The flag name moved across vLLM versions. By default the entrypoint AUTO-DETECTS it
# from `vllm serve --help` (prefers the modern --structured-outputs-config.backend,
# falls back to --guided-decoding-backend, else relies on vLLM's xgrammar default).
# Only set this to force a specific flag:
# STRUCTURED_OUTPUTS_FLAG=--structured-outputs-config.backend  # vLLM 0.10+ (current)
# STRUCTURED_OUTPUTS_FLAG=--guided-decoding-backend            # older vLLM

# Per-agent LoRA adapters: space-separated name=path (path under /models/lora/...).
# The `name` is what a PydanticAI agent puts in the OpenAI `model` field.
# NONE EXIST YET — leave empty until fine-tunes land. On 12 GB keep MAX_LORAS small.
LORA_MODULES=
# LORA_MODULES=file-edit=/models/lora/file-edit git-ops=/models/lora/git-ops
MAX_LORAS=2
MAX_LORA_RANK=16          # must be >= the rank used in training

# Model storage is a WSL2-backed Docker *named volume* (`remora-vllm-models`), mounted
# read-only at /models — NOT a host bind mount. This keeps multi-GB weights in the fast
# WSL2 ext4 filesystem, off the Windows/NTFS drive, so there is no host path to set here.
# When MODEL is an HF repo id (the default), weights download into the `hf-cache` volume
# automatically — nothing to pre-stage. To serve LOCAL safetensors / LoRA adapters,
# populate the volume before `docker compose up`:
#   docker volume create remora-vllm-models
#   docker run --rm -v remora-vllm-models:/models -v <your-weights-dir>:/src:ro alpine \
#     cp -r /src/. /models/
# Layout inside the volume:  /models/base/<safetensors>  and  /models/lora/<adapter>/

# --- Client side: point the library + live tests at THIS service ------------
# These are NOT consumed by the container; they're for the host running the test
# suite / spike. They mirror the server settings above: LLM_API_KEY == VLLM_API_KEY,
# LLM_MODEL == SERVED_MODEL_NAME (or a LoRA name from LORA_MODULES).
#   export $(grep -E '^LLM_' deploy/vllm/.env | xargs)   # load them into a shell
# then run the live tests (see deploy/vllm/README.md):
#   SAV_LIVE=1 devenv shell -- uv run --extra dev pytest -q -m live
LLM_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000/v1
LLM_API_KEY=change-me                 # keep in sync with VLLM_API_KEY
LLM_MODEL=base                        # SERVED_MODEL_NAME, or a LORA_MODULES name
